SIMPLE: loosen
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loosen
<hw>Loos"en</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧s"'n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Loosened</conjf>
<pr>(l⟦oomac⟧s"'nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Loosening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Loose</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make loose; to free from tightness,
tension, firmness, or fixedness; to make less dense or compact; <as>as,
to <ex>loosen</ex> a string, or a knot; to <ex>loosen</ex> a rock in the
earth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After a year's rooting, then shaking doth the tree good by
<qex>loosening</qex> of the earth.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To free from restraint; to set at
liberty..</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>loosens</qex> his hands, and assists his
understanding.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To remove costiveness from; to facilitate or
increase the alvine discharges of.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loosen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Loosen
<hw>Loos"en</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become loose; to become less
tight, firm, or compact.</def> <rj><au>S. Sharp.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>loosened</ent>⟦br⟧
